  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Syrian refugees emergency response2</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Conflict in Syria has now been ongoing for 2 yrs resulting in the displacement of 136,000 refugees in to Iraq by the end of April&apos;13. The majority are in the Kurdistan region, and some in the Governorate of Anbar. Most of the refugees are of Kurdish origin and are settled in camps managed largely by UN agencies in collaboration with Iraqi authorities or in damaged and insufficient shelters in urban areas and host communities. Needs of the displaced families are identified as including health, protection, education and basic items for their day to day requirements. This emergency project will meed immediate needs of families to improve access to hygiene and increase their resilience in coping with their displacement.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Since the earlier project, REACH has been carrying out further assessments for refugees in off-camp locations in Sulaimaniya and Erbil, and priority needs identified. Assessment activity will continue during the project implementation, as the influx of refugees is expected to continue and to prioritise support to the most vulnerable households. REACH&#x2019;s approach is to target the most vulnerable in the community and they will work with the beneficiary groups to identify and target their work with them. They use a vulnerability and capacity framework which consists of an analysis of the problems and people&#x2019;s capacities to address them. Planned interventions are for 500 health &amp; hygiene kits, 250 NFIs, and food for 2,100 families.</narrative>
  </description>
